    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#mohamed-jmr1997"/>, pp. 38-39 n. <citedRange>14</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>47.2190</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>087400</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.76</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Νικάθλα"><supplied reason="lost">Νικά</supplied>θλα</name> <g type="punct">⋮</g> 
                        <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Αἰγλάνωρ" type="patronymic">Αἰγλάνορος</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1"><lem><supplied reason="lost">Νικά</supplied>θλα <g type="punct">⋮</g></lem>
                        <rdg resp="#mohamed-jmr1997"><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Κριτ</supplied>όλα <note>the first editors did not mention the punctuation</note></rdg>    
                    </app>
               </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Nika</supplied>thla fille d'Aiglanôr.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Nika</supplied>thla daughter of Aiglanor.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Nika</supplied>thla figlia di Aiglanor.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Reading the first preserved letter as an omicron, the first editors thought of a woman's name of the group corresponding to masculine compounds in 
                    <foreign xml:lang="grc">-λαος</foreign>, of which the suggested <foreign xml:lang="grc">Κριτολᾶ</foreign> is only one amongst other possibilities.
                    We know in fact of a woman of that name, also daughter of an Aiglanor, who was priestess of Hera in the first century AD (see <ref type="inscription" target="https://ircyr2020.inslib.kcl.ac.uk/en/inscriptions/C.129.html">IRCyr2020 C.129</ref>).
                    However, the gap in time is too big to allow any relation between them. In fact, C. Dobias-Lalou reads the first preserved letter as a theta with a large circle and a thin central dot, whereas both omicrons are smaller. The masculine name 
	           <foreign xml:lang="grc">Νίκαθλος</foreign> is well attested and typically Cyrenaican (see <bibl><ptr target="#jmr-masson1976"/>, p. <citedRange>92</citedRange></bibl>).
	           So a feminine <foreign xml:lang="grc">Νικάθλα</foreign> is a guess matching exactly the gap.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
